			<note place="foot" n="1"> Our chosen albedo value for HAT-P-7b is an order of magnitude greater than the albedo reported by Esteves et al. (2013), but is required to match the Kepler observations of this system: since OoT neglects thermal emission from the planet, geometric albedo is the only lever to increase the amplitude of variations at the orbital frequency. This subtlety is immaterial to the current analysis, however: neither reflectance nor thermal emission from a static planetary map can contribute odd harmonics at the levels reported for these planets, as shown by Cowan et al. (2017) and illustrated in the insets of Figure 1. Moreover, the time variations in albedo reported for HAT-P-7b (Armstrong et al. 2016) are far too slow to account for the observed odd mode amplitude (Cowan et al. 2017).</note>
